nadian fatherhood has changed dramatically over the past several decades. Shifting family structures, policy issues, and cultural expectations affect men's interactions with their children and influence the way they perceive their own roles as fathers. The traditional notion of fatherhood may have changed, but fathers are as important today as ever before. Father Involvement in Canada brings together more than a dozen leading scholars of fatherhood issues to examine the roles of Canadian fathers from many angles. Looking at the experiences of fathers from different ethnicities, age groups, marital statuses, gender partnering, and economic brackets, the authors examine issues such as the impact of poverty, access to paternity leave, and the availability of support from social institutions. National in scope, this is the first book of its kind to summarize and challenge current scholarship on Canadian fatherhood and offer new concepts, theoretical frameworks, and research directions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFatherhood -- Canada. 0aFathers -- Canada. 7aFAMILY & RELATIONSHIPS / Parenting / General.2bisacsh1 aAllen, James W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllen, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBala, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBall, Jessica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBall, Jessica, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBeaton, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Leslie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCallahan, Marilyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaly, Kerry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.go